#Approach:

💡 IDEA
- Friends circle me baithe hain.
- Har round me k-th friend eliminate hota hai.
- Queue circular movement ko simulate karegi.
- First (k-1) friends ko front se nikaal kar rear me daal do.
- Jo k-th friend front par aayega, usko remove kar do.

⚙️ APPROACH
1. Queue me 1 se n tak saare friends daal do.
2. Jab tak ek se zyada friend bache:
   - (k-1) times:
     front friend ko rear me move karo.
   - Ab front par k-th friend hai.
   - Use remove kar do.
3. Last remaining friend winner hoga.

📝 EXAMPLE

n = 5
k = 2

Initial:

[1,2,3,4,5]

----------------

Move 1 friend

2,3,4,5,1

Remove front

remove 2

Queue:
[3,4,5,1]

----------------

Move 1 friend

4,5,1,3

Remove front

remove 4

Queue:
[5,1,3]

----------------

Move 1 friend

1,3,5

Remove front

remove 1

Queue:
[3,5]

----------------

Move 1 friend

5,3

Remove front

remove 5

Queue:
[3]

Winner = 3

❓ WHY QUEUE
- Queue naturally circular movement simulate kar sakti hai.
- Front se nikaal kar rear me daalne se clockwise rotation ho jata hai.
- Elimination process exactly queue operations se match karta hai.

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Time  : O(N × K)

Reason:
- Har elimination ke liye (k-1) rotations.
- Total (n-1) eliminations.

Space : O(N)

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- Circular traversal ko queue rotation se simulate karte hain.

  temp = q.poll();
  q.offer(temp);

- (k-1) rotations ke baad:
  Front = k-th friend

- Front ko remove karna hi elimination hai.

- Ye Josephus Problem ka simulation-based solution hai.

- Mathematical Josephus solution O(N) me hota hai,
  but queue simulation interview me sabse intuitive approach hai.

#Code:

import java.util.*;

public class Solution {
    public int findTheWinner(int n, int k) {
      //You can code here
      Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();

      for(int i=1; i<=n; i++){
        q.offer(i);
      }

      while(q.size() > 1){

        for(int j=1; j<=k-1; j++){
          int temp = q.poll();
          q.offer(temp);
        }

        q.poll();
      }
      
      return q.poll();

    }
}
